data.title: Snowflake Stock Rises after Q4 Beat, Goldman Sachs analyst cuts target to $216, Needham analyst to $200.
data.description: Shares of Snowflake Inc (NYSE: SNOW) surged in early trading on Thursday following their positive fourth-quarter results. Analyst insights revealed from various reports include Goldman Sachs' Gabriela Borges maintaining a Buy rating and reducing the price target to $216 from $246. Needham's Mike Cikos also upheld a Buy rating but lowered the price target from $280 to $200. Blair Abernethy of Rosenblatt Securities maintained a Buy rating with a $275 price target. According to Goldman Sachs, Snowflake exceeded product revenue expectations by 2% and surpassed EBIT margins by 350 basis points. Despite some concerns post-earnings, with worries about guidance conservatism, the company is seen as having the potential to exceed Street estimates through increased product revenue acceleration. Snowflake’s expansion of its monetizable surface across its AI Data Cloud is expected to contribute to this.For further details, the full story can be accessed on Benzinga.com.

data.title: Pet Supplies Plus wins Bronze Stevie® Award for customer service in 20th annual awards, nation's largest pet retail franchise.
data.description: A leading pet retailer based in Livonia, Michigan, was recently honored in the 20th Annual Stevie Awards for Sales & Customer Service. This recognition highlights the company's dedication to providing outstanding customer support.

data.title: TP reports 2025 results with a new CEO to execute strategic plan, with top executives stepping down by March 15, 2026.
data.description: In Paris, TP (Paris:TEP) has announced a new governance strategy to enhance the execution of their strategic plan. Jorge Amar, a reputable expert in AI-native customer operations on a global scale, has been appointed as Group CEO. Current executives Daniel Julien and Thomas Mackenbrock will step down from their roles, with Julien also resigning from the Board of Directors on March 15, 2026. Olivier Rigaudy, responsible for finance, will also step down as Deputy CEO. Additionally, four new members will be co-opted to the Board of Directors.

data.title: Health Gorilla files Motion to Dismiss lawsuit by Epic, reaffirms commitment to interoperability for safe data exchange.
data.description: In Coral Gables, Florida, Health Gorilla has taken a significant step by filing a Motion to Dismiss a lawsuit brought against them by Epic. In this legal action, Health Gorilla has emphasized its dedication to robust interoperability frameworks that facilitate the secure exchange of patient data among providers throughout the country. The Motion to Dismiss argues that the lawsuit launched by Epic is viewed as a threat to interoperability, potentially jeopardizing patient well-being and the effectiveness of healthcare services at a national level.
